-- Japanese, Australian Stock Futures Advance on Yen, Higher Commodity Prices
-- Kotaro Tsunetomi
-- 2010-07-20T23:39:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/japanese-australian-stock-futures-advance-on-yen-higher-commodity-prices.html

          
          
             Japanese and Australian  stock 
 futures  rose after the dollar strengthened against the yen and
higher commodity prices boosted material producers.  
 American depositary receipts of  Sony Corp. , a Japanese
electronics maker that earns more than 20 percent of sales in
the U.S., gained 1.4 percent from yesterday’s closing share
price in Tokyo. Those of Toyota Motor Corp., a Japanese carmaker
that gets about 70 percent of its sales abroad, rose 0.4 percent.
ADRs of Canon Inc. advanced 1.1 percent after the Nikkei
newspaper said the company raised a forecast for revenue from
some digital cameras. Those of  BHP Billiton Ltd. , the world’s No.
1 mining company, jumped 2.3 percent from the Sydney close.  
 “The global economy is slowing down, but concern about a
double-dip recession is fading,” said  Hiroichi Nishi , an
equities manager in Tokyo at Nikko Cordial Securities Inc.  
 Yen-denominated futures on Japan’s Nikkei 225 Stock Average
expiring in September closed at 9,380 in Chicago yesterday,
compared with 9,305 in Singapore. Futures were bid in the pre-
market at 9,390 in Osaka, Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time.
Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index advanced 0.9 percent
today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index rose 0.3 percent in Wellington.  
 Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  rose less than
0.1 percent today. In New York yesterday, the index erased early
losses to gain 1.1 percent on speculation Federal Reserve
Chairman Ben S. Bernanke will take steps to spur lending and
after a report showed a faster-than-estimated increase in
building permits, a gauge of future construction.  
 Yen, Commodities  
 After U.S. trading closed, Apple Inc. reported third-
quarter profit that exceeded analyst estimates as customers
began flocking to its new iPad tablet computer and the latest
version of the iPhone telephone.  
 The yen depreciated to as low as 87.58 against the dollar
today in Tokyo from 87.04 at the close of stock trading
yesterday. A weaker yen boosts the value of overseas income at
Japanese companies when converted into their home currency.  
 The MSCI Asia Pacific Index has declined 4.2 percent this
year, compared with drops of 2.8 percent for the S&P 500 and 3
percent for the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the Asian
index are valued at 14 times estimated  earnings , compared with
13.2 times for the S&P 500 and 11.5 times for the Stoxx 600.  
 Crude oil for August delivery rose 1.2 percent in New York
yesterday, the highest settlement price since June 28. The
London Metal Exchange Index of six metals including copper and
zinc gained 1.7 percent yesterday, rising for a second day in
its biggest increase in two weeks.  
